        .4u class="12u$(medium)"
          header
            h3 There's nothing wrong with <br>the Agile Manifesto.
            p <br/><b> We extend its <a href="http://agilemanifesto.org/">values</a> and <a href="http://agilemanifesto.org/principles.html">principles</a> to oppose bureaucracy and disorganization. Not altering the original, but adding on:
            h3 &nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Descaling Values</u>
            ul
              li <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/leadership-service-peter-merel/" target="_blank">Autonomy and alignment</a> <br>over command and control
              li <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/tragedy-pmo-peter-merel/" target="_blank">Throughput accounting</a> <br>over cost accounting.
              li <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/fixed-price-agile-transformation-peter-merel/" target="_blank">Pull-based delivery and change</a> <br>over push-based
              li <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/samurai-tea-master-peter-merel/" target="_blank">Learning ecosystems</a> <br>over training hierarchies.
              br While there is value in the items on the bottom, we value the items on the top more. And ...
        .4u class="12u$(medium)"
          h3 &nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Descaling Principles</u>
          p
            h5
              ol#selector
                li Directly responsible individuals: business, design and tech stakeholders make decisions together as peers to build solutions that meet each others' constraints.
                li Capture and store learning in small, self-organizing teams: as these work with current constraints they become capable of opening future bottlenecks.
                li Work on outcomes: teams continuously prioritize the current bottleneck, quantify their contributions to top line business throughput, and minimize work in progress.
                li Align small groups of teams into self-managing business streams that continuously adapt their work priorities to changing market feedback.
                li Reward mutual benefit across business streams to reduce silos, wastes and missed opportunities, and share resources, services and learning.
                li Mercilessly refactor business streams: reuse, recycle or reduce all the resources a stream produces so all contribute to top line throughput and none go to waste.
            ul.actions
              div style="text-align:center"
                a.button.special href="#signatory"  Sign The Descaling Manifesto
        div class=("4u$ 12u$(medium)")
          h3 &nbsp;
          p
            h5
              ol start="7"
                li Design breadth-first. Step back to see patterns in and between markets and value streams. These inform designs we can only detail as we learn more.
                li Collaborate rather than delegate: people and teams are in the right relationships when conversations evolve to support each-others' work and learning.
                li Take time to simplify and automate solutions: simple, automated systems cost less than big manual ones, taking less work to maintain business outcomes.
                li Use and value experimentation: experiment to reduce risk and adapt each product to the changing constraints of your business streams and markets.
                li Enrich interfaces to serve under-served markets: spaces between market segments are where most opportunities for innovation and productivity occur.
                li Transform to embrace change: continuously adapt your organization's patterns to changing market conditions and opportunities to open new markets.
            p
              | Like the agile and permaculture manifestoes this is based on, we regard the above as <a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BwhCYaYDn8EgN2M5MTkwM2EtNWFkZC00ZTI3LWFjZTUtNTFhZGZiYmUzODc1/view" target="_blank">closed to modification but open to extension</a>. Not the last word but the next.</b>
